      "status": "skipped",
      "actions": [],
      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(tools): surface empty availability group diagnostics via onHiddenDiagnostic callback",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nEmpty or malformed plugin tool `availability` groups (e.g. `{ anyOf: [] }`, `{ allOf: [\"bad\"] }`) silently hid the tool from the plan with no diagnostic. This adds an `onHiddenDiagnostic` callback so `resolvePluginTools` can surface those as authoring warnings, and preserves plugin-authored availability metadata so the planner can evaluate and warn instead of dropping it silently.\n\nFixes #92361.\n\n## Current diff (warn-only, 6 source files)\n\n- `src/tools/types.ts` — add `onHiddenDiagnostic?` to `BuildToolPlanOptions`.\n- `src/tools/planner.ts` — invoke `onHiddenDiagnostic` for each diagnostic that hides a tool.\n- `src/tools/availability.ts` — replace the key-presence `hasAvailabilityExpressionShape` with `isValidSignalShape`, which validates `kind` plus the required fields per signal type and rejects non-array `allOf`/`anyOf`.\n- `src/plugins/tool-descriptor-cache.ts` — `readAgentToolAvailability` preserves availability-like records so malformed groups still reach the planner/warn path instead of being dropped at capture.\n- `src/plugins/tools.ts` — wire `buildToolPlan` + `onHiddenDiagnostic` into `resolvePluginTools`; guard `collectAuthProviderIds`; resolve manifest control-plane enabled plugin ids.\n- `src/plugins/manifest-contract-eligibility.ts` — `resolveManifestControlPlaneEnabledPluginIds` helper.\n\n**Not in this diff:** there are no `src/plugin-sdk/*` changes — an earlier SDK-export iteration was dropped. The current behavior is warn-only diagnostics, not a fail-closed/SDK-contract change.\n\n## Crash guard (addresses the P1 review finding)\n\n`collectAuthProviderIds` walks nested `allOf`/`anyOf` entries, which — because `readAgentToolAvailability` intentionally preserves malformed records for the planner to warn on — can be primitives or `null`. It now returns early on non-object/`null` before any `in` check:\n\n```ts\nif (!availability || typeof availability !== \"object\") {\n  return;\n}\n```\n\nso `{ allOf: [\"bad\"] }` / `{ anyOf: [null] }` no longer throw before diagnostics are emitted. A follow-up commit also guards self-referential availability cycles.\n\nRegression coverage: `resolves tools without throwing when availability holds malformed nested entries` drives `{ allOf: [\"bad\", null] }` through `resolvePluginTools` with `hasAuthForProvider: () => true` (the exact crash path the review flagged).\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed:** empty/malformed availability groups were hidden with no diagnostic; malformed nested entries could additionally crash `resolvePluginTools` during auth-provider collection. After this change the planner emits an authoring diagnostic and the collector no longer throws.\n\n**Environment tested:** Node v22.22.0 on Linux, branch `fix/92361-tool-availability-empty-group-warning`, head `b49789bc3f90fceea666ef6b9d138f3f5bbc0465`.\n\n**Evidence after fix:**\n\n`isToolAvailabilityExpression` validation:\n\n```text\nvalid allOf: true\nnon-array allOf: false\nnon-array anyOf: false\nallOf non-expr entries: false\nanyOf non-expr entries: false\n```\n\n`resolvePluginTools` with empty `anyOf` (authoring warning surfaced, not silently hidden):\n\n```text\nempty group tools=\n[plugins] tool descriptor authoring error (proof-plugin/proof_tool): Empty availability anyOf group\n```\n\n**Verification on head `b49789bc3f9`:**\n\n```text\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/tools/planner.test.ts src/plugins/tool-descriptor-cache.test.ts src/plugins/tools.optional.test.ts src/tools/availability.test.ts\n  -> 100 passed\n\nnode scripts/run-tsgo.mjs -p tsconfig.core.json --incremental false\n  -> exit 0\n```\n\n**What was not tested:** live gateway startup against a real external plugin package shipping malformed availability metadata.\n\n## Compatibility note\n\nThis starts preserving plugin-authored `availability` metadata that current `main` and `v2026.6.9` ignore during descriptor capture, surfaced as warn-only diagnostics. Hidden tools behave as before; the only added behavior is the diagnostic warning. Maintainers should explicitly accept the warn-only semantics (or select an overlapping sibling implementation for #92361).\n",
        "branch": "fix/92361-tool-availability-empty-group-warning",
        "head_sha": "031868f4a8b92eb492b5500ee3056667f3c7feb1",
